Let me start with the conclusion: In my personal opinion, “Sihai” is a completely terrible movie in every sense.
But if you say this movie doesn’t have any highlights at all, that’s not quite true either; at least the soundtrack is quite good.
There are many types of bad movies, and the ones that make you fall asleep soundly in the cinema are one category; those that leave you filled with indignation after watching are another. “The Four Seas” is like the monkeys on Mount Emei to the audience—it can ignite your anger in countless ways.
Han Han truly has an extraordinary talent when it comes to insulting the audience.
The most painful aspect of this film is that it seems to be a creation out of a Krishna-related novel—indescribable in nature, and riddled with flaws, just like the trench coat worn by the character Maugham.
Even after watching it, you might wonder if there are any hidden metaphors imposed by the director… But upon further reflection, you realize that it’s actually just a pile of shit.
Let me first briefly explain some plot elements that I find really difficult to understand.
Her grandmother had a wish to see snow, and so the plot arranged for an elderly man from the neighborhood to drive her there in a small van to the northeast to experience the snow.
Are elderly people traveling from the south to the northeast in a van to see the snow???
And then that old man’s story just ends there, with no further development.
How did the female protagonist’s brother obtain the business license to open a hotel on an abandoned ship?
Why are those little troublemakers from the biker gang on the island able to easily block off a section of the mountain road??
Then the truck that was delivering steel bars in the middle of the road stopped by the side of the road, and not even the truck driver could be found anywhere around.
The sense of “prop” (i.e., an object that’s not part of the natural environment or the character’s body) is just too obvious, isn’t it?
How could a small-time thug with a poor credit record and suspected involvement in illegal activities become a police officer on a part-time basis?
Why don’t they call the police when facing usury? In the movie, the police even specifically ask if there are any difficulties.
An adult knows how to use a smartphone, but doesn’t know how to open a hotel room door with a card. Then they try to force their way into the room because they can’t find the hotel owner, and end up sleeping outside the room door for the night?
These utterly inexplicable plot elements are present throughout the entire film, and because they are so absurd, recalling them causes me great distress.
Apart from the plot, what’s even worse is the main theme of the movie—or rather, the fact that the movie doesn’t have any real theme at all. It’s just a repulsive, stitched-together mess.
At the beginning of the movie, you might think he wants to make a comedy. After about 20 minutes, you might guess it could be an inspirational film. Halfway through, you start to think it might be a drama that aims to show the difficulties young people in a small town face. By the end, you’re completely confused about what you just watched, which leads to deep self-doubt. Why on New Year’s Day would you go to the cinema to watch something that’s basically just… well, nothing special?
For most people, the tropes of different types of movies are actually quite familiar. For example, if you want to make a movie about a motorcycle rider, it usually follows a formula that combines elements of inspiration and comedy, while showing the audience how a talented newcomer gradually achieves success step by step.
If you want to make a love story movie, then just honestly tell the story of the complex relationships between a young guy from the town who likes riding motorcycles and a waitress girl.
If you want to reflect reality, then at the very least your plot shouldn’t contain anything that contradicts the normal world.
(For example, the character played by Yoon Jung, whose new motorcycle just got burned down but who can still sing…) One shouldn’t come up with such crazy ideas that even Kennedy wouldn’t be able to handle.
As for the female protagonist, who clearly isn’t mentally disabled but behaves in some ways like a 5-year-old child, I really don’t know whether it’s due to her acting skills or the director’s requirements.
There’s another thing I really can’t understand: Why is Han Han, as a racing driver, so keen on including car crash scenes in his own movies?
Is such a movie arrangement during the Spring Festival season really meant to cause trouble for the audience?
