Yesterday, journalists learned from the Municipal Education Commission that starting this year, our city will pilot a “modern apprenticeship system” for talent development in 60 secondary vocational schools. Students participating in this program will have both the status of apprentices and, after being admitted, will be pre-employed by the participating enterprises as regular employees.
Pilot schools need to reform the model of talent cultivation.
Schools and enterprises jointly design talent training programs, establish professional teaching standards, curriculum standards, job-related standards, standards for enterprise mentors, quality monitoring standards, as well as corresponding implementation plans.
The pilot program is designed to last for one academic cycle. The duration of students’ internships at companies is determined according to the professional training programs, with a typical internship period lasting six months.
In corporate practices, a team-based management model should be implemented. Depending on the characteristics of different professions, one master can guide 2 to 5 apprentices, forming learning groups to ensure that students acquire the necessary skills for each training position proficiently.
According to the plan, from 2016 to August 2019, our city identified 60 pilot projects for the modern apprenticeship system at the municipal level in three batches. Each pilot project involved approximately 50 participants, resulting in the training of around 3,000 students (apprentices) in total.
Following the principle of piloting first and then implementing, and progressing gradually from point to area, efforts should be made to establish a long-term mechanism for joint enrollment, joint training, and integrated education between schools and enterprises. This will effectively enhance students' job-related skills, increase their employment rate in relevant fields, and improve the quality of their employment.
