Recently, an emergency information release platform for missing children, developed by the Anti-Trafficking Office of the Criminal Investigation Bureau of the Ministry of Public Security, was launched.
This is an internet information platform created to establish an authoritative channel for releasing information about missing children and to help locate abducted children in a timely manner.
Hearing that the app is called “Reunion,” I immediately feel a warm sensation.
The new technological methods are not only named in a “literary” and emotionally rich way, but also make proper use of information technology; they are practical and effective.
The primary goal of anti-trafficking law enforcement is to recover the abducted children and ensure their personal safety and freedom.
Only afterwards comes the trial and punishment of the suspect.
The significance of criminal punishment can be discussed in terms of various aspects, ranging from individual punishment and social prevention to legal education. There are many important concepts that can be mentioned in this context.
However, before the trafficking case is solved, priority should be given to ensuring the personal safety of the victims.
We need to prioritize matters based on their urgency. Under the pressing need for “rescue,” topics that are highly controversial and have varying opinions, such as whether child trafficking should always be punishable by death, can be put aside for more careful consideration; however, the rescue of abducted children cannot wait.
Based on the experience in investigating such cases, human traffickers tend to leave the crime scene as soon as possible after they have achieved their goals.
With every additional minute wasted in the search for a kidnapped child, the child moves further away from their parents, and the difficulty of solving the case increases accordingly.
In this situation, taking an effective approach such as the “Reunification” platform, which directly helps to solve the case and find the child, is indeed a pragmatic move.
After all, "combating trafficking" is a major task that requires the entire legal system to be put in operation in order to be effectively carried out.
To combat crime and protect the rights of children and parents, it is essential to implement a comprehensive approach that encompasses the improvement of legislation, the provision of judicial safeguards, and the meticulous enforcement of laws. All these efforts must be guided by the principle of caring for the vulnerable and supporting those in need.
Furthermore, the prevention of child trafficking can be improved further, from the family level to society as a whole.
For example, in a common scenario, a family of three is resting at the train station. The parents are fast asleep, and when they wake up, they realize that their child is missing.
You can’t expect a two-year-old child to have sufficient self-protection skills, but as the parent of such a young child, you should at least have a decent level of awareness about how to protect them.
It is the most basic measure to prevent children from being abducted: either parents take turns resting, or the children are placed in a safe and secure environment under protection.
From another perspective of the police’s efforts to combat trafficking crimes, the side that purchases the abducted children should also be addressed and punished.
A single illegal act is often just one link in a much longer chain of events.
According to the provisions of our country’s Criminal Law, the minimum penalty for the crime of trafficking in children is 5 years in prison; in particularly serious cases, the punishment can be death, accompanied by the confiscation of property.
With a high threshold for prosecution and severe maximum penalties, the crime of trafficking children clearly falls under the category of offenses that are subject to more stringent punishment, in line with the general trend towards leniency in sentencing.
Yet, to this day, a considerable number of cases of trafficking still occur every year.
It is evident that some people have outdated views on raising children and a weak sense of legal awareness.
The legal education for this group of people should be provided in a concurrent manner.
To effectively control the crime of trafficking, we cannot rely solely on strict law enforcement by the authorities.
Therefore, breaking down outdated notions and promoting legal knowledge can also help to effectively eradicate the crimes of child trafficking and purchase.
Yang Haodong delivered a lecture on the spirit of the Sixth Plenary Session of the 19th Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and the Provincial Party Congress at Malanshan.
Yang Haodong explained the core essence and practical requirements of the plenary session's spirit in a comprehensive and systematic manner, from three aspects: ideals and beliefs as well as the original mission; self-revolution and the role of the party as a youthful force; and the party's leadership and theories. He did so by combining his own insights and personal experiences, using simple and clear language to make the concepts accessible to all.
