Extra virgin olive oil, also known as natural olive oil, is obtained by mechanically cold pressing fresh olive fruits. The oil is then filtered to remove any impurities.
Depending on the acidity level, they can be divided into three categories:
Extra Virgin Olive Oil: This is the highest quality and finest grade of olive oil, and it is a completely natural product.
The taste is excellent, with a subtle and pleasant fragrance of plants; the acidity does not exceed 1%.
Fine Virgin olive oil: It has a slightly higher acidity, but not exceeding 2%. The taste is pure and aromatic.
Refined olive oil refers to the olive oil obtained after the refining of virgin olive oil with an acidity level exceeding 3.3%, and is also known as “second-grade oil”.
Refined olive oil can be divided into two grades:
Regular Olive Oil: A blend of refined olive oil and a certain proportion of extra-virgin olive oil, designed to balance the flavor and color. It has an acidity of less than 1.5% and appears as a clear, pale golden yellow liquid.
Refined Olive-Pomace Oil: This is an olive oil that is obtained by extracting it from the oil residue using a dissolution method and then undergoing refinement processes.
Those who have looked at the grading systems should have already realized that the acidity of olive oil is a very important indicator.
You should know that olives are similar to the grapes used for making wine; olives from different regions and varieties will produce olive oil of varying quality.
The best locations for the growth of oil olives are:
The Mediterranean coast possesses the most ideal soil conditions, as well as the right climate parameters such as temperature, sunlight, air humidity, and precipitation levels required for the growth of olive trees.
Apart from the Mediterranean coast, in other areas, it can only be grown sporadically in suitable habitats.
Months of harvesting oil olives:
From March to June each year, the olive trees bloom and set fruit. From July to October, the fruit begins to develop and ripen, changing color from green to red, then purple, and finally to black.
The fruit-picking season is from November to February of the following year (the freshness of olive oil is really important!).
Nutritional components of olive oil:
Olive oil is rich in monounsaturated fatty acids, namely oleic acid, linoleic acid, and linolenic acid, as well as vitamins A, B, D, E, K, and antioxidants.
Olive oil is considered to be the most suitable fat for human nutrition among all the oils that have been discovered to date.
