I want to give tennis a try, but I’m afraid I won’t be able to stick with it long enough. So, I’m looking for a training device that’s reasonably priced to get started with.
Unfriendly, in fact. Prices are often directly proportional to the level of “friendliness” (i.e., the quality or user-friendlyness of a product). If you can’t tell the difference, it’s normal for more expensive products to be more friendly (in terms of quality) than cheaper ones. These so-called “entry-level” products are actually just industrial waste.
They have very low strength; when the ball hits the racket, the vibrations are extremely intense. Hard balls can’t withstand these vibrations, and even experienced players find it difficult to control them.
The logic and underlying message behind this are as follows: Tennis is such a difficult sport that we knew you wouldn’t be able to learn it, and we also knew you wouldn’t be willing to spend a lot of money on a good racket. So we came up with a cheap alternative to trick you into buying it. After playing with it a couple of times, you’ll probably stop playing tennis altogether. Since the racket is cheap, you won’t feel too bad about wasting your money.
When you’re really able to tell the difference between good and bad things, it will mean you’ve made progress. Then you can come to me and buy the expensive ones – that way I’ll make money twice over.
I suggest spending a similar amount of money on a used tennis racket of better quality. Choose a brand like Prince or Dunlop; these are not very well-known, so even a good racket from these brands won’t be too expensive. A new racket can cost around 500–600 yuan, while a used one can cost just 200 yuan. Wouldn’t it be great to enjoy the performance of a racket that’s worth thousands of yuan, but at a much lower price?
It’s quite friendly to beginners, but becomes useless once they’ve passed the beginner stage. However, most people, especially women, don’t manage to overcome the beginner phase.
