In Hangzhou’s Wulin Square, a girl stood in front of a large wooden board that read, “Human Target; ten yuan per arrow.”
Yesterday morning, a photo showing a girl from Hangzhou willingly acting as a “target” to raise funds for her sister went viral on social media.
The photo shows a girl in Hangzhou’s Wulin Square standing in front of a large wooden board that is slightly taller than her. On the board is written “Human target, ten yuan per arrow,” indicating that passersby can use a bow and arrows to shoot the target after making a payment.
This behavior has sparked a heated discussion among netizens.
Last night, the person in charge of publicity at the Xiaceng Branch of the Hangzhou Public Security Bureau confirmed to a reporter from The Beijing News that the police had indeed acted in such an extreme manner to raise funds for the girl’s sister. However, such behavior is not advisable. After being admonished, the girl left the local police station yesterday.
In the picture circulating online, a girl with long hair is standing in a “V” shape in front of a large wooden board. On the board, the words “Human target; 10 yuan per arrow” are written in black ink. On another wooden board in front of her, her bank account numbers, as well as her WeChat and Alipay account information, are listed.
The image sparked controversy after it was uploaded to the internet.
Some netizens believe that this action is a form of “attention-seeking begging,” while many others express sympathy for the individuals involved.
In an interview with local media, police officers from the Tianshui Police Station near the incident site stated that there were two girls setting up stalls, both around 20 years of age and dressed in a youthful and attractive manner.
Among them, the girl who was used as a “human target” kept crying and begged passersby to play this game. Another girl was standing by, helping to spread the message and saying that her friend’s sister had leukemia and urgently needed money for surgery; she asked everyone to please help.
Last night, the person in charge of publicity at the Xiaceng Branch of the Hangzhou Public Security Bureau told a reporter from The Beijing News that the girl’s name is Jijiali, and she was collecting donations for her sister Jijiayan.
However, since the treatment still costs over 300,000 yuan, and no good way to raise the funds has been thought of immediately, such an action was taken.
He said that throughout the entire process, one of the two girls served as a target, while the other acted as an assistant but did not actually participate in the activity. No one was observed shooting arrows; instead, people just watched and took photos, which were then posted on Weibo.
Subsequently, the police, with the assistance of the public security department, determined that the bow and arrows used did not fall under the category of items subject to regulation.
The person in charge stated, “This type of attention-grabbing fundraising method is not advocated.”
After being warned by the police officers at the police station, she has left the station.
