What was the biggest hit in 2021?
There’s no doubt it’s the Tokyo Olympics.
Do you think only Olympic athletes can win awards?
Some time ago, an article titled “Look! Project Managers Can Compete in Olympic Events for Gold Medals” became very popular. It mentioned that project managers can definitely take the lead in many projects, with no one being able to match them: carrying heavy loads, traveling on business, staying up late are all part of their daily routine, and stepping in to fix problems, taking the blame, and apologizing are just second nature to them.
An article that seems like a joke or mockery actually reveals the daily hardships faced by project managers, reflecting the sense of powerlessness in current project management practices.
And the personnel engaged in project management are also gradually choosing to take certain actions in order to get out of the difficulties they face at work.
Judging from the increasing number of applicants for the PMP (Project Management Professional) certification each year, it is evident that more and more professionals in the field of project management are improving their skills through education.
In the past 10 years, the number of PMP (Project Management Professional) certifications has been increasing year by year. This indicates that more and more project managers are realizing that relying solely on traditional methods and past “experiences” is no longer effective. The rapidly changing work environment teaches us that we must learn from the achievements of scientific pioneers and build upon their knowledge to find new ways forward.
However, does obtaining the PMP certification guarantee that project management work will proceed smoothly without any obstacles?
Many beginners in project management say that by taking courses related to PMP/IPMP, they can systematically learn about the ten knowledge areas and five process groups of project management. However, when it comes to actually carrying out project management work, they still find themselves completely confused.
Many project managers often report the following issues: - A lack of proper understanding of project management principles; relying solely on personal experience, while possessing only theoretical knowledge without knowing how to apply it in practice. - The absence of a systematic project management process and supporting systems, making it difficult to implement effective methods in work. As a result, project estimates are inaccurate, control mechanisms are ineffective, and projects are constantly delayed. - Unclear division of responsibilities among team members, and those with more experience don’t know how to effectively manage new or challenging situations. - Poor cross-departmental communication, which hinders the progress of
