This year, during the “Double Eleven” shopping festival, the total amount of transactions in online payment services across the country reached 1.77 trillion yuan, setting a new record compared to previous years.
The diverse range of promotional red envelopes offering discounts and bonuses, along with the eye-catching live-streaming sales events, have once again enabled consumers to feel that they are getting a great deal. On one hand, this surge in consumption highlights the growing purchasing power of the nation’s citizens; on the other hand, it also forces us to take a more cautious look at the impact of consumerism on society and the contemporary mainstream consumer group.
As Double Twelve approaches, Credit Suisse reminds all consumers to develop a reasonable sense of spending and a correct attitude towards money. It urges them to resist impulsive and excessive consumption, as well as to avoid common pitfalls in consumer lending, in order to prevent negative impacts on their personal credit records and future financial well-being.
When making purchases, it is essential to plan in advance, spend within your means, and repay the loans on time.
If the payment is overdue, the overdue record will be included in the individual’s credit report, which could have negative implications on future financial activities such as purchasing a car or a house.
At the same time, when enjoying financial products and services, it is important to choose legitimate institutions and channels, and to verify whether the relevant institutions have the necessary qualifications to operate.
