The so-called "university spirit" refers to a series of educational philosophies and value pursuits that have been gradually established over the long term during a university's development process; it represents the very essence of the university.
From ancient times to the present, the spirit of universities has been of paramount importance for the development of politics, economics, culture, technology, society, and even the progress of a nation as a whole.
Since the birth of the world’s first modern university, universities have undertaken a unique mission that sets them apart from other social organizations. For the universities in our country, which emerged during times of national crisis, their spirit has been profoundly influenced by traditional culture and the changes of the times. They advocate for the values of “cultivating virtue to benefit society” and “improving oneself, regulating one’s family, governing the state, and bringing peace to the world,” as well as the patriotic commitment to “strengthening the nation through education.”
Currently, the trends of informatization and internationalization in higher education are becoming increasingly evident. The competition in education, technology, and talent on a global scale is intensifying. As a crucial “supply-side” component of higher education, this sector is facing unprecedented opportunities and challenges in terms of structural reform.
In particular, the introduction of the "Comprehensive Plan for Promoting the Development of World-Class Universities and Disciplines" demonstrates our country's confidence and determination in transitioning from a major player in higher education to a powerful nation in this field. It also sets even higher and more modern requirements for the development of universities.
It is particularly important to recognize that building world-class universities cannot mean that all universities should look the same. While each university should leverage its strengths, it must also showcase its unique personality and characteristics.
The distinctive features of a school should not only reflect the common Chinese characteristics but also embody each school's unique goals, educational traditions, and resource endowments.
In this process, it is particularly important to always uphold the university spirit and ensure that it resonates in harmony with the spirit of the times.
For Zhejiang University, the motto “Seeking Truth and Innovation,” the shared values of “Diligent Learning, Cultivating Virtue, Clear Discrimination, and Sincerity,” as well as the mission statement “Embracing All Rivers and Streams, Promoting Truth and Virtue, Advancing Society, and Strengthening Our Nation,” collectively constitute the latest expression of the university’s spirit.
This is an important guarantee for the school to maintain the correct direction in its educational efforts, continuously build up a high level of cultural heritage, and foster a strong sense of community spirit. It is rich in meaning and has far-reaching implications.
This series of spiritual concepts and value pursuits is precisely the essence of Zhejiang University’s 120-year history of education.
“The wise hear what is silent; the discerning perceive what has yet to take form.”
Chinese universities should further focus on the overall situation of the cause of socialism with Chinese characteristics, deeply understand the historical context in which higher education operates and the mission they bear, and accelerate their efforts to become world-class institutions.
