The Qinghai Lake naked carp, commonly known as the “Huang fish,” is a unique and precious species found only in Qinghai Lake. It plays a vital role in maintaining the safety of the “water-fish-bird” ecological chain and biodiversity within the Qinghai Lake basin.
In the 1960s and 1970s, due to factors such as massive human hunting and the deteriorating environmental conditions in the areas where the Qingshai Lake naked carp were bred, the population of this fish species declined sharply. By 2002, the reserves of Qingshai Lake naked carp had dwindled to just 2,592 tons.
In 2004, the Qinghai Lake naked carp was listed as an endangered species in the “China Species Red List”.
Since 2003, Qinghai Province has implemented a policy of closing lakes to promote fish reproduction. No entity, collective, or individual is allowed to fish for the naked carp in Qinghai Lake or its main rivers and tributaries, and the sale of naked carp and its products is prohibited.
Meanwhile, efforts to protect the resources of the Qinghai Lake naked carp have been continuously intensified through measures such as artificial propagation and reintroduction into the lake, cleaning of the main rivers flowing into the lake, and the design of scientifically sound and reasonable “fish passages.” As a result, the stock of naked carp in Qinghai Lake has been increasing year by year.
Yang Lin, the deputy director of the Qinghai Provincial Department of Agriculture and Rural Affairs, introduced that as of now, nearly 180 million naked carps have been artificially propagated and released into Qinghai Lake, contributing more than 23% to the recovery of the naked carp population in the lake.
The Sanjiangyuan area in Qinghai is an important ecological barrier and water conservation region for not only China but also for Asia. Lake Qinghai serves as a natural barrier that prevents the desertification in the west from spreading eastward, as well as fulfilling important ecological functions.
In order to protect the ecological environment of the Sanjiangyuan area and the Qinghai Lake basin, as well as the aquatic wildlife, and to maintain the biodiversity of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, Qinghai has issued notices prohibiting fishing in key waters of the Yangtze River, the Yellow River, and Qinghai Lake since the beginning of this year. As a result, a comprehensive fishing ban management system has been established for each river and lake.
