Just saw an article about menstruation; it was too long.
Here’s some basic information for men who may not know about this:
Most girls experience their first menstrual period suddenly at some point between the ages of 13 and 15, and menopause occurs around the age of 50.
After that, assuming good health, it will occur fairly regularly once a month.
But it’s not predictable with such precision that a exact schedule can be made. There’s usually a margin of about a week, so you need to prepare in advance. Sometimes, bad luck can cause things to go wrong (for example, the event might be moved up by several days unexpectedly).
The duration of symptoms, the amount of bleeding, and the severity of menstrual cramps vary from person to person. Some people experience symptoms for three days, while others for a week; some have light bleeding, while others suffer from heavy bleeding. Some people don’t experience any noticeable discomfort, while others are in so much pain that they need to be transported to the hospital by ambulance. Menstrual cramps can change over time—just because someone didn’t experience pain in the past doesn’t mean they won’t experience it in the future.
The menstrual flow is uncontrollable; there is bleeding 24 hours a day for several days from the start to the end. The only thing that can be done is to use sanitary pads or tampons to absorb the blood and prevent it from soiling clothes or furniture.
Cramps during menstruation are mainly caused by the secretion of prostaglandins. Taking ibuprofen as soon as menstruation begins can effectively relieve the pain for that month; taking it after the cramps have already started is not very useful.
Before menstruation, due to the increased blood flow in the uterus and the excessive release of prostaglandins, diarrhea is more likely to occur.
If it’s around the time of your period and you suddenly start having diarrhea for no obvious reason, your period will probably start within two days.
It’s best to change sanitary pads every two to three hours; otherwise, bacteria can easily grow. Excluding the time spent sleeping, in the worst-case scenario, you would need to change them 6 times a day. With 7 days in a month, that amounts to 42 pads. If you also include some extra pads that you prepare in advance, you might end up with around 50 pads in total. It doesn’t mean that you use one pad per month.
(The text should be revised as follows: Tampons don’t need to be changed frequently; they can usually be replaced every five to six hours, at the longest every eight hours.)
During menstruation, hormonal fluctuations can make one more irritable. Similarly, around the time of ovulation, emotional instability may occur due to changes in hormone levels in the body. It’s just unfortunate; the body seems to create its own obstacles for us.
However, the official crime rate data shows that women have a high ability to control their emotions and do not use emotional issues as excuses.
What is flowing is not just blood; it also contains the shed endometrium.
The endometrium is thinnest after menstruation and gradually thickens again. You can think of the uterus as a “house” that is “built” every month (the endometrium thickens) in preparation for “guests” (the embryo). If the “guests” do not arrive, the entire structure is dismantled (menstruation occurs), and then a new “house” is built the following month, and this cycle repeats continuously.
Menstruation can be extremely inconvenient. For decades, women have to go through several days of bleeding every month, 24 hours a day, in addition to experiencing abdominal and back pain. Who would want that?
But a person can be born because his mother had her periods. Menstruation serves to prepare the body for the 10 months that the baby will spend in it after being born. Everyone should be grateful to their mothers for having regular and healthy menstrual cycles.
In the past, many aspects of women’s lives were suppressed, and society brainwashed women into believing that certain behaviors were dirty and shameful. Everyone just accepted that as the truth, but times have changed.
If anyone finds menstruation disgusting, or thinks that the female body’s preparations for conceiving a life are repulsive, they shouldn’t speak about such things in public. Girls, stand up and stop thinking that way. You’ve never experienced it, and you probably never will; nor do you really understand it. Men who have never experienced it either, please don’t be so ungrateful and insensitive. How can you even have the nerve to face your own mothers with such an attitude, or to want to have children of your own?
Finally, sisters, give tampons a try; they really work well.
