Hunan Daily, December 10th (Reported by All-Media Journalists Zhang Shangwu and Hu Panpan; Correspondents Liu Xiaoling; Photography by Li Jian) This morning, the 13th Hunan Tea Industry Expo and the Xinhua Black Tea Promotion Event were held at the Hunan International Convention and Exhibition Center. The event aimed to showcase the tea industry, promote innovative tea technologies, foster tea culture, and accelerate efforts towards achieving a tea industry worth 100 billion yuan.
Hou Shunli, Deputy Director of the Council of the All-China Federation of Supply and Marketing Cooperatives, and Ye Hongzhuan, Deputy Director of the Standing Committee of the Provincial People's Congress, attended the opening ceremony.
Professor Liu Zhonghua, an academician of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, made a prominent announcement at the opening ceremony: The origin of Huhong tea lies in Xinhua, and the rise of black tea has injected new momentum into the development of “Wucai Xiangcha” (a variety of Hunan tea).
In recent years, the provincial Party committee and government have provided strong support for the development of the tea industry, promoting the construction of a tea industry worth hundreds of billions of yuan. As a result, a development pattern characterized by "tea from three regions of Hunan and four types of water, with a variety of colors" has been established.
The fortunes of feng shui change with the times, and black tea is making a comeback once again.
Experts in the tea industry within the province state that by harvesting green tea, followed by black tea and dark tea, tea farmers can generate income throughout the year, and the value of tea plantations continues to rise steadily.
During the opening ceremony, provincial leaders awarded plaques to the fourth batch of enterprises authorized to use the “Hunan Black Tea” trademark, with Xinhua being honored as the “Source of Huhong” (the name for Hunan black tea).
At the Xinhua Black Tea Exhibition Hall, a Fujian tea merchant took a liking to a high-mountain tea variety called “Bingli Chun” and placed an order on the spot.
The Xinhua black tea, with its distinctive red hue, has infused new meaning into the tea culture. It is highly popular and generates brisk trade, bringing a new spring to the Hunan tea industry.
