Ding Zilin: To a friend.
I would like to express my sincere gratitude to all my friends for the humanitarian assistance they have provided over the past 30-plus years, since the tragic loss of our loved one. This assistance has continued without interruption, especially since I personally issued a call for help to friends both at home and abroad in early 1994.
These days, the parents of the vast majority of the deceased have passed away, and the orphans have grown up, started families, and found employment.
It was your acts of kindness that helped us, these families in distress, through the most difficult times.
Currently, the COVID-19 pandemic is raging around the world, and most of the donors have reached retirement age.
Therefore, I earnestly request you to cease making humanitarian donations to us, the Tiananmen Mothers group. This act of humanitarian assistance should have come to a perfect end a long time ago.
I will always remember your kindness, and I firmly believe that your righteous deeds will be remembered by history.
For various reasons, I can only express my wishes in this way. Please understand, friends!
I send you my sincere blessings.
(Apple Daily photo: The Tiananmen Mothers website is managed by Tao Ye.) pic.twitter.com/UxID9ZGjzm
Relief funds often do not make it smoothly to the hands of the victims of the 1989 Tiananmen incident.
Since 2018, it has also received support from the Foundation for Research on Labor Reform.
It was not until last year, after a wait of 31 years, that the survivors of the June 4th incident finally received a portion of the funds that had been donated in their name back then from Hong Kong.
We understand that Teacher Ding decided to stop the donations for the June 4th event out of consideration for the donors. After all, we are all retired individuals whose incomes are not as substantial as they were before retirement. Therefore, we would like to express our gratitude for Teacher Ding’s letter “To Friends”.
Thanks and respect also go to those brave and generous individuals who have, for many years, taken the risk of delivering humanitarian aid funds.
