Let’s take a look at some of the [strange trending searches] today.
What is considered a normal public opinion?
Randomly select three trending searches: “The Dragon Raising Ceremony on the Second Day of the Second Lunar Month,” “The price increase of Good Luck Friends (a snack brand),” and “The Huolala incident.” Public opinion spreads, forming a peak, followed by a [decrease in the index] (represented by a smooth curve), and eventually the trend dissipates. If secondary public opinion reactions occur, a small surge in interest may reappear.
They look exactly the same as the [Network Public Opinion Evolution Model] that was previously displayed on the official website of the Cyberspace Administration of China.
What is abnormal public opinion?
Randomly select six trending searches from the same event, and present them in the forms of “isolated peak,” “zigzag,” and “cliff.”
In Figure 9, the peak of popularity for one event coincides precisely with the trough of popularity for another event, down to the very second. This must indicate that a group of coordinated “water army” (internet trolls or botnets) was given a task to launch a new round of attacks.
The专业化 of black public relations is evident in this case: dozens of trending topics make it onto the list simultaneously. These topics are carefully selected to either attract attention, disseminate scientific knowledge, stir up controversy, divert attention, influence perception, mislead judgment, arouse emotions, or influence decision-making. The accounts belonging to these black propaganda networks operate in a meticulous and strategic manner, dividing their efforts into batches and at specific moments, taking into account almost all factors involved in the spread of public opinion.
Communication is a science. By setting aside all subjective factors such as opinions and emotions, and focusing solely on objective data, even black PR (negative public relations efforts) will have no place to hide.
Everything that passes leaves a trace, and we dig those traces out together.
Data source: The Hot Search Time Machine.
