Starry Sky Appointment | The Geminid Meteor Shower will reach its peak on the 14th – Xinhua News Agency
Xinhua News Agency, Tianjin, December 12 (Reporter Zhou Runjian) According to experts in astronomy and science popularization, the Geminid meteor shower, one of the three major meteor showers in the Northern Hemisphere and also the last large-scale meteor shower of the year, will reach its peak on December 14. Friends who enjoy watching meteor showers can observe it in the second half of the night on that day.
The Geminid meteor shower, photographed by An Jiu, an astronomy enthusiast from Beijing, on December 13, 2018, in Qinghai.
The Geminid meteor shower is also the second known meteor shower that is not originated by a comet.
Xiu Lipeng, a member of the Tianjin Astronomical Society and an expert in popularizing astronomy, explained that, just like the blockbuster New Year’s films, the Geminid meteor shower usually occurs at the end of the year, with its “screening period” lasting from December 4th to December 17th.
A notable feature of the Geminid meteor shower is the relatively slow speed of the meteoroids, as well as their rich variety of colors and the presence of many fireballs. This makes it an excellent option for both casual stargazers and beginners in astrophotography.
The Geminid meteor shower, photographed on December 13, 2020, by Yang Jing, an astronomy enthusiast from Tianjin, in Jizhou, Tianjin.
Astronomical forecasts indicate that this year’s Geminid meteor shower will reach its peak around 15:00 on December 14th, with a ZHR (Zenith Hourly Rate) of 150. The ZHR represents the number of meteors that can be seen per hour under ideal observation conditions, when the radiant point of the meteor shower is directly above the observer’s head.
Graph showing the recommended index for the Geminid meteor shower.
The 14th falls on the 11th day of the 11th lunar month, which is a waxing gibbous moon phase. The bright moonlight can interfere with observations. Fortunately, the moon will set in the second half of the night, and at that time, the radiant point of the Geminid meteor shower will also be higher in the sky.
Friends who enjoy meteor showers can observe them in the hours after the moon sets in the early part of the night, but be sure to keep warm to avoid catching a cold.
How can one observe as many meteors as possible?
It’s important to note that the Geminid meteor shower has a high rate of meteors coming from various directions, so there’s no need to constantly focus on the radiant point of the shower during observation.
Friends who enjoy photography and want to capture stunning ‘meteor shower’ images should opt for a wide-angle lens with a large aperture. When shooting, use a high ISO setting and the maximum aperture of the lens.
Considering stability and durability, a tripod, spare batteries, and a remote control for the shutter are also essential.
What are the differences in market positioning between laser TVs and traditional TVs?
From what I understand, the traditional TV mentioned by the questioner should refer to a liquid crystal display (LCD) TV. The main differences in market positioning between laser TVs and LCD TVs are as follows:
Firstly, laser TVs are more focused on the large-screen market.
Compared to the market positioning of LCD TVs, which are widely available, laser TVs seem to focus more on the large-screen market. In other words, laser TVs are essentially products designed for large screens.
Currently, the sizes of mainstream LCD TVs range from 55 inches to 65 inches, while laser TVs generally have a size of 75 inches or more, with the largest models exceeding 100 inches. This fully meets users' demand for large-screen color televisions.
In recent years, the shipment volume and sales share of laser TVs have been continuously increasing worldwide. They account for more than 60% of the total sales of TVs with a screen size of 80 inches or larger.
The reason for such excellent results in the large-screen market is mainly due to the outstanding eye-care features of laser TVs.
Based on the principle of imaging through diffuse reflection in laser TVs, the light emitted by the laser source does not directly enter the eyes. Compared to the backlight of liquid crystal TVs, this imaging process is more similar to the way objects are perceived under natural conditions, resulting in less irritation to the eyes.
Experts from the CCSTC Saisi Laboratory and the Ophthalmology Department of Peking Union Medical College Hospital conducted a rigorous comparative study in which participants watched both laser TVs and LCD TVs under the same conditions. As a result, 144 sets of test data were collected.
The data confirms that laser TVs indeed have strong eye-protecting properties and can even have a positive effect in certain aspects.
In an era where vision health is receiving increasing attention, laser TVs have not only attracted more and more users due to their benefits for eye care but have also opened up a new breakthrough in the color TV market.
Secondly, laser TVs are more targeted at the high-end market.
Contrary to the continuous decline in the prices of LCD TVs, the prices of laser TVs currently available on the market are mostly over 10,000 yuan. As the screen size and the light source improve, the prices are gradually increasing.
Why are laser TVs so expensive?
There must be some logic to it.
With the continuous advancement of light sources and technological levels, laser TVs possess many advantages that liquid crystal TVs and projectors are unable to achieve.
Thanks to their ultra-short-throw projection technology, laser TVs require a much shorter projection distance compared to traditional projectors. This allows for a 100-inch large-screen experience at a close range, while occupying minimal space. Additionally, the main unit of the laser TV is compact and takes up very little room.
In terms of brightness, high-end brand laser TVs can achieve luminosities of over 2000 lumens.
Furthermore, with a lower heat generation, there is less wear and tear on the equipment, resulting in a longer lifespan for the television.
In addition to this, many high-end laser TV models are equipped with various cutting-edge technologies such as true 4K ultra-high definition resolution, artificial intelligence systems, and bio-inspired displays, providing users with an even more stunning visual and auditory experience.
It’s not so much a case of “pseudo-demands” as rather the result of a more detailed segmentation of market needs. In terms of image quality and cost-effectiveness, laser TVs are not the right choice for audio-visual enthusiasts. If you want to combine a large screen with a suitable viewing environment but face limitations in this regard, you can still give it a try. Everything has its pros and cons; you should make your own judgment after weighing all the factors. The main thing to avoid is taking things at face value or believing only one side of the story.
In simple terms, ultra-wide-angle, short-throw projectors (such as laser TVs) have to use expensive ultra-wide-angle lenses and mirrors in order to get the image close to the screen. This does not conform to the principles of optimal optical design.
In order to block some of the ambient light, using a microstructured Fresnel screen comes at a high cost; the price of an 80-inch screen is roughly equivalent to that of a 65-inch LCD screen.
One more thing: I really hate it when projector manufacturers use the argument that diffused light is good for the eyes as a selling point. Seriously, the light from the screen that the eyes see is actually direct light. Even if the light is diffused and then hits the ceiling, the eyes can’t see it. Moreover, LCD TVs also emit diffused (but still direct) light; doesn’t the ceiling get illuminated when the TV is turned on?
Moreover, if the projection screen does not exhibit diffuse reflection, it simply cannot form an image.
It’s precisely the heat spot (light spot) effect of high-gain screens that is often overlooked. A large amount of light reflected at a certain angle into the eyes is what really causes discomfort.
