Is it reliable to buy insurance for a small umbrella?
“Xiao Yu San” is an internet-based insurance brokerage platform.
These three requirements are actually quite stringent. In summary, a company must possess the necessary capabilities and obtain approval from the authoritative national regulatory body, the China Banking and Insurance Regulatory Commission (CBIRC), which oversees insurance companies and banks nationwide. The shareholders of such a company must also have a good reputation. As an insurance brokerage firm, Xiaoyusan Insurance provides assurance that policyholders need not doubt the legitimacy of the company. After all, with these three barriers in place, not just any insurance company can meet them.
In this regard, it’s not bad at all; it’s trustworthy.
From the perspective of insurance products: Xiaoyusan Insurance acts as an “insurance supermarket,” where many well-known critical illness insurance policies from various companies are sold. For example, the recently launched Hetai Super Mary 5 Critical Illness Insurance is available on this platform, with both the claims processing and underwriting parties being Hetai Life Insurance. As a third-party intermediary, there’s no need to doubt the reliability of Xiaoyusan Insurance.
From the perspective of payment methods: Products offered by internet platforms have a higher cost-performance ratio due to the elimination of operational expenses for physical stores and employee salaries. The payment options are also flexible, including monthly payments, which reduces the financial burden on policyholders. Additionally, this approach allows for maximum leverage in the use of insurance as a risk management tool.
This is really quite good.
It can be considered.
In terms of the professionalism of sales representatives: This is particularly important because the insurance industry requires a high level of expertise. Many internet-based products allow customers to purchase insurance on their own, which can lead to numerous misunderstandings. When it comes to health-related information and employment history, individuals who are not from the insurance industry often add their own subjective judgments when applying for insurance, assuming they are healthy or meet the required criteria. This can result in potential issues with claims processing and an increased risk of being denied compensation.
I have personally worked in insurance telemarketing for “Tencent Weibao” (similar to Xiaoyusan, it is also an internet-based insurance brokerage platform). I can tell you with all sincerity that the job requires a high level of responsibility.
Insurance for the internet is indeed real and reliable; it’s the people who can be unreliable. Internet channels often lack professional staff, and there are also many cases of misleading sales practices.
For example: an insurance policy that costs 1 yuan provides coverage of up to 6 million yuan; buying the insurance comes with a free mobile phone; or customers can get an additional 60,000 yuan in coverage for serious illnesses for free. These marketing strategies are not wrong in themselves, but they tend to focus on the positive aspects and avoid mentioning the important details. Policyholders are not informed that the initial fee of 1 yuan is just for the first month, and from the second month onwards, regular charges will apply, ranging from several tens to 200 yuan per month. As a result, many
Thinking I could spend just 1 dollar, and the insurance company would pay out 6 million (it’s like finding a gold mine right in front of me).
The free phone is offered only for special policy numbers, such as 6666 or 8888. If you win the prize, you will receive a notification message, but you have to exchange it yourself; no one else will remind you to do so.
(This is another pitfall for policyholders.) Getting a free coverage of 60,000 yuan for serious illnesses is only temporary. If you rely solely on this and have no other commercial insurance, what good will the 60,000 yuan do if you actually suffer from a serious illness? It won’t solve the problem, and your life will then be in a very difficult situation.
The state is also taking strict action against the misleading information regarding the sale of internet insurance.
So, taking everything into account, there is no problem with the platform or the product; the issue lies with the professionalism and ethical standards of the sales representatives.
It is recommended that the person asking the question consider all the options carefully. In fact, many traditional insurance brokerage companies offer a wider range of products, giving customers more choices and options to consider. Some of these products also provide better value for money compared to those available online.
I have personally helped 59 internet customers with underwriting offline products, enabling them to save between 2,000 and 3,000 yuan per year on their insurance premiums.
If anyone has any questions, feel free to communicate and interact with me.
I: Mingya Insurance Broker, with 3 years of experience in corporate management training. I have served nearly a thousand corporate clients and collaborated with over 100 insurance companies. Before purchasing insurance, I start by understanding the client's needs and customize an insurance product tailored to their specific requirements. During the purchase process, I help them compare different options to ensure they get the best possible underwriting outcome. After the purchase, I take care of organizing and managing their insurance policies, ensuring they can stay worry-free.
Grow together with every customer throughout their entire life.
I hope my answer can be of some help to the person who asked the question!
According to the definition provided by insurance regulatory authorities, internet insurance refers to an insurance product where the policyholder can independently complete the entire application process by clicking on the relevant application link.
In this process, the policyholder does not need to sign anything, nor does the insurance advisor need to sign anything; all steps can be completed independently by the policyholder.
Although the process of purchasing insurance online doesn’t involve much of a “formal ceremony,” and there might not even be a printed paper contract, this in no way affects the validity or legal significance of the electronic contract.
This model is somewhat similar to the assembly-line process used in telemarketing. However, there is a fatal flaw with this approach to purchasing insurance: the subsequent services provided may not be up to par.
Insurance is usually a long-term contract that lasts for several decades. When we purchase insurance, shouldn’t we seriously consider whether the “intermediary” we choose is someone who can be by our side for a long time and continue to provide us with services even after many years?
